                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.5914/79</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Copenhagen</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-08-07T17:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 7, 1916, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>289. Referring to the Legation’s number 287, August 7, 3 p.m. Foreign Office
                    informs me that first publicity came to Copenhagen in a despatch from Ambassador
                    Jusserand to Bapst, French Minister here. Bapst is the only one of my colleagues
                    who openly finds our policy of buying Danish West Indies objectionable. He tells
                    Foreign Office that it may lead to buying of Martinique.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Egan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
